courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students shall be able to:

1. Recognize major quantitative and qualitative methods in social science;
2. Identify and formulate research questions of a research proposal;
3. Select and collect a body of academic literature which is relevant to the research questions;
4. Describe and explain relationships between the selected independent and dependent variables;
5. Apply research design relevant to the research questions;
6. Compare and contrast the strength and weakness of each method;
7. Produce an empirical research proposal;
8. Use statistical software to organize and analyze quantitative data on an introductory level;
9. Reflect critically his or her own research and those of other social science research papers and

policy reports;
10. Identify possible societal, political, economic and organizational dynamics that would affect

research processes;
11. Follow codes of ethics while designing and implementing the research proposal.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
a. To gain insight into the economic nature, sources, dynamics and impacts of FDI;
b. To possess an awareness of the factors impinging on public policies towards FDI and their effectiveness;
c. To gain insight into the nature of MNEs, their role in the global economy, their structures, their strategies, and their operations;
d. To obtain an appreciation of their multiple impacts, both favourable and unfavourable, on host economies;
e. To understand their complex and evolving relationships with governments and other regulatory agencies.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1) understand the development of the currency war and its impact on the global system;
2) understand the rising importance of China from a currency perspective in the context of the currency war;
3) learn about the future development of China’s political and financial development in preparation for accommodating the new China in the business, investment and academic sectors.

After completing this course, students should be able to:
1. appreciate that environmental problems are inextricably political economic questions;
2. describe and explain the global dimensions of contemporary environmental changes, in terms of their roots, processes and implications;
3. describe, compare and evaluate the assumptions and interpretations of key theories of global environmental politics, and
4. apply theories of global environmental politics to analyse the roles and strategies, and costs and benefits of different actors and institutions in the production and regulation of global environmental changes.

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:

1) Acquire knowledge of the relationship between Hong Kong, Macao and mainland China;
2) Analyze the significance of Hong Kong and Macao in furthering China's foreign interests;
3) Explore future developments in Hong Kong-Mainland relations and Macao-Mainland relations; and

4) Reflect upon the significance of such freedom in furthering the interests of the Greater China Region to the uniqueness of Hong Kong and Macao

After the completion of this course, students should be able to:
Learning Outcome 1: Understand the historical and theoretical background of European integration project;
Learning Outcome 2: Evaluate the dynamics of EU institutions and their relations to EU member states;
Learning Outcome 3: Conceptualize EU external presence and its relations to major powers; and
Learning Outcome 4: Reflect upon contemporary issues faced by the European Union and its Member States by various conceptual lenses

Upon completion of this course, students will be able to:
1. Acquire knowledge of Chinese foreign policies towards various issues such as territoriality,
war and conflict, and development;
2. Analyze the implications of Chinese foreign policies for its relations with other countries;
3. Explore the roles of China in the context of its rise as a power.
4. Understand the impacts of China’s rise on the international system and global governance

The main objective of this course is to equip students with an adequate grasp of China’s goals and decision-making processes in relations to Beijing’s enhanced global power projection, particularly its growing role in the international political economy. A key understanding of China’s objectives and strategies ranging from reshaping the world’s financial order to boosting investments in intercontinental infrastructure projects will enable students to gain fresh perspectives on China’s fast-changing economic and political ties with international institutions as well as major countries and regions.

After taking this course, students should be able to fully understand – and be able to form their own views on:
• The goals of Chinese foreign and national-security policies; and ways in which Beijing seeks to play a bigger role in reshaping the international financial order;
• China’s strategies of enhancing its leadership capacity in global institutions and forums;
• Beijing’s ambitious projection of financial power through massive overseas investment as well as boosting inter-continental infrastructure projects;
• The pros and cons of major policy agendas such as the Belt and Road Initiative – as well as formidable challenges that they face;
• Chinese concerns and game plans regarding the formation of free trade zones and handling global issues such as climate change, commodity prices and food security;
• The pillars of the “China model” and the quasi-superpower’s drive to promote innovation in government systems as well as the industrial and services sectors.

Students should be capable of not only making informed analysis but also formulating their own theories and hypotheses regarding the full range of topics. For example, students should use IR and global political economy theories to assess the degree of success of China’s financial and trade-related “great leap outward.” Such prognosis and prognostication should be based on references to latest journal and news publications, ideas introduced by the lecturer, as well as debates within classes among advocates of different viewpoints. Guest lecturers who are practitioners in the finance, think-tank, and diplomatic sectors might be invited to give talks to students.

Upon completion of the course, students will be able to:

·acquire experience working both independently and collaboratively with a team of policy professionals;

·develop transferable skills for work or further study (e.g. data and policy analysis);

·better understand how to apply theoretical knowledge to solve social/economic/political challenges and problems; and

·identify how theoretical knowledge can be improved through empirical research and direct experience.

